definition : A  function  from a set $A$ to $B$ is a binary relation where every element in $A$ corresponds to exactly one element in $B$. We write,   
    f: A \to B   "$f$ is a function from $A$ to $B$".  We typically define functions using equations (e.g. $f(x) = x^2$) but they can also be lists.  Example   
\begin{aligned}
    A &= \{ 1,2,3,4 \} \newline
    B &= \{ w,x,y,z \} \newline
\end{aligned}

\begin{aligned}
    f &= \{ (1,x), (2,y), (3,w), (4,y) \}
\end{aligned}   This is a function since everything in $A$ corresponds to one thing in $B$. It's okay for multiple things in $A$ to go to one thing in $B$.

\begin{aligned}
    g = \{ (1,x), (2,y), (3,z) \}
\end{aligned}   This is  not  a function since $4$ is not mapped to anything.

\begin{aligned}
    h = \{ (1,x),(2,x),(3,x),(4,x) \}
\end{aligned}   This is a function.

\begin{aligned}
    i = \{ (1,y),(2,z),(2,x),(3,w),(4,x) \}
\end{aligned}   This is  not  a function since $2$ corresponds to two values.

